article.description:
Deron Williams  had 24 points and seven
assists for Utah in a 96-93 win over the Timberwolves -- the team's first win streak in a month.
article.headline: Jazz finally win back-to-back games, beat Wolves
article.linkText: Jazz finally win back-to-back games, beat Wolves
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- After going nearly a month without winning consecutive games, the Utah Jazz are finally on a winning streak. They couldn't have waited much longer. "We're trying to make the playoffs. That's our goal. We think we can do it," said Deron Williams, who had 24 points and seven assists for Utah in a 96-93 win over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday. "It's not like we're six or seven games out." Utah improved to 30-31 and got within three games of Denver for first place in the Northwest Division. The Jazz have 21 games remaining. Andrei Kirilenko had eight blocks and eight assists to go with 15 points and 11 rebounds. Matt Harpring also scored 15 for the Jazz, who hadn't been on a winning streak since Feb. 10 and have been booed a few times lately at home. Team owner Larry Miller berated his team after a five-point win over Orlando on Monday, when the Jazz had blown a 20-point margin before holding off the Magic. There was plenty to criticize again in Wednesday's victory, but coach Jerry Sloan defended his players. "I realize we can do a lot better and the expectations are there, but the important thing is that you do things right so you have a chance to win," Sloan said. Sloan met with Miller earlier in the day and was reassured that his job wasn't in jeopardy. Miller was irate when the Jazz collapsed late in Monday's game and was overheard saying "fire" to two team executives during a timeout. Miller said before Wednesday's game he meant the Jazz lacked intensity and he didn't threaten to end Sloan's 18-year run in Utah. "I want Jerry to coach this team," Miller said before the game. Minnesota is also running out of time to make a playoff push. The Timberwolves lost for the second straight night and fell to 26-34 when Trenton Hassell's 3-pointer at the buzzer missed everything. Reserve Marko Jaric scored 20 points for Minnesota, which didn't score in the first 5 minutes of the third quarter. "We didn't have one of the best third quarters. Third quarters have been our Achilles' heel," said Kevin Garnett, who had 26 points and 13 rebounds. "In the second half, we didn't have that same flow." Still, the Timberwolves had a chance at the end thanks to some shaky free throw shooting by Utah. Kirilenko went 1-for-2 from the line four times in the fourth quarter and Williams went 1-for-2 with 6.2 seconds left. Minnesota got within 90-88 on a tip-in by Ricky Davis, then got another break when Kirilenko went 1-for-2 from the line with 53 seconds left to put the Jazz ahead 91-88 Garnett made a jumper from the lane get the Timberwolves within a point again, but Carlos Boozer, who scored 12, got a layup around Garnett with 22 seconds left and Harpring extended the lead to 95-90 with two more free throws with 10.4 seconds left. Davis kept Minnesota alive on a 3-pointer with 8.1 seconds to play, but Williams' free throw was enough to force the Timberwolves to go for a 3 at the end. "We had chances to come back, tie the game and force overtime but we didn't," Jaric said.< Game notes
Minnesota only used eight players. ... Kirilenko tied his career high for blocks and also had two steals. ... Milt Palacio scored 11 for the Jazz. ... Utah hadn't won two games in a row since beating Chicago on Feb. 6 and following that four days later with a victory at Minnesota.
